            <Title>Introduction to JavaScript Object Notation (JSON)</Title>
            <Text>Introduction to JavaScript Object Notation (JSON)

JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is a information exchange standard that can be a used as an efficient alternative to eXtensible Markup Language (XML) by using JavaScript syntax rather than tags.
JSON is not part of the ePub standard, though it used by ebookbuild to store the e-book metadata and the page order in each project’s metadata.json file. I chose this format because it’s human-readable and an open standard that is natively supported by the Python programming language (among others).
In the current version of ebookbuild, the metadata.json file has to be modified manually. I plan on implementing a graphical user interface (GUI) frontend that makes retrieving and editing the e-book metadata even faster in the future.
Here is an example of a metadata.json file:



JSON Syntax

Objects
“An object is an unordered set of name/value pairs. An object begins with {left brace and ends with }right brace. Each name is followed by :colon and the name/value pairs are separated by ,comma.”
- Introducing JSON, JSON.org

Most of a JSON file consists of objects which are defined with a name and then a value.

Arrays
“An array is an ordered collection of values. An array begins with [left bracket and ends with ]right bracket. Values are separated by ,comma.“
- Introducing JSON, JSON.org

Arrays are a collection of JSON objects with consistent attributes. I use an array to define the page order.


Comments
Comments are not supported by JSON, though I have created a series of JSON objects called “comment” such as “comment1”, “comment2”, “comment3”. Keep in mind these are live data and can be manipulated as such.


Further reading:

JSON.org - official website with information about the standard and many of its libraries for use in programming language


