            <Title>Introduction to CSS</Title>
            <Text>Introduction to Cascading StyleSheets (CSS)

Cascading StyleSheets (CSS) is a stylesheet language used to define the appearance of HTML (and by extension, XHTML) elements. CSS facilitates beautiful e-book typesetting and should be the forefront of an e-book’s design.
It is best to use external CSS where the classes are defined with one or several dedicated .css files. However, I will demonstrate the two other ways of adding CSS to an e-book project.

In-line CSS via the style attribute

Note: In-line CSS definitions are recommended solely for prototyping CSS classes and should not be used in production.

Each XHTML tag supports the “style” attribute, which facilitates in-line CSS definitions. This means CSS attributes can be applied to an individual tag without creating a CSS class. For example, adding bold and italic to span tag:

&lt;p&gt;The cat &lt;span style=”font-weight: bold; font-style: italic”&gt;sat&lt;/span&gt; on the mat.&lt;/p&gt;

The cat sat on the mat.

In a real e-book project, I would combine the bold &lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt; and italic &lt;i&gt;&lt;/i&gt; tags instead of using a span to create bold italic for emphasis. 

Internal CSS via the head tag

Note: Internal CSS definitions are recommended solely for prototyping CSS classes and should not be used in production.

Internal CSS uses the style &lt;style&gt;&lt;/style&gt; tag within the head tags to define one or more CSS classes for a specific XHTML file.

&lt;head&gt;
	&lt;meta content=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml; charset=utf-8&quot; http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot;/&gt;
	&lt;title&gt;Acknowledgements&lt;/title&gt;
	&lt;style&gt;
		span.bold-italic {
			font-weight: bold;
			font-style: italic;
		}
	&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;

&lt;body&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;The cat &lt;span class=”bold-italic”&gt;sat&lt;/span&gt; on the mat.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;

External CSS via a dedicated .css file

References:
https://www.w3schools.com/css/css_howto.asp</Text>
