Text editor
A text editor is needed to create and then edit the XHTML, CSS and metadata.json files. Most of the time spent on an e-book will be using a text editor so it’s important that you can find it comfortable and easy to use.
Text editors may be the most common type of computer program with many options to choose from and I am aware of just how defensive some users can be of their preferred text editor (especially the vi vs. emacs editor wars).
Back at Oxford eBooks, we used Notepad++ for the bulk of our text editing. Notepad++ has an outdated user interface and is restricted to Microsoft Windows. For those reasons I consider Atom and Visual Studio Code to be suitable replacements. 
An appropriate text editor for e-book development should support the following features:

Syntax highlighting for XHTML, CSS, JSON and Markdown.
Find and replace with regular expressions

Visual Studio Code
# Microsoft Windows, macOS, Ubuntu
Visual Studio Code is my preferred text editor for several years.


Terminal emulator
Both macOS and GNU/Linux have an excellent preinstalled terminal which requires little modification except cosmetic changes such as the font size and background colour.
For Microsoft Windows I recommend installing Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL) which allows installation of a minimal GNU/Linux environment including the Bash shell.

Windows Terminal
# Microsoft Windows

Windows Terminal is the terminal emulator I’ve been waiting for and I was eagerly awaiting its stability when I first tested it in 2019. 
It is pre-installed on Windows 11. For Windows 10, it is recommended to install via the Microsoft Store, though it can be downloaded and installed manually or even compiled from source code in Visual Studio.


Git client
Git is a popular version control system (VCS) and I recommend using it for e-book development because it organises your workflow and backs up your work. In this book I have provided a dedicated Introduction to Git and GitHub chapter for information Git clients and how to get started with Git if you are complete newcomer.

GitHub Desktop
